Multilevel leaf decomposition model example

Bob Hall

8 March 2023

The problem

We want to measure leaf decomposition in 6 streams that vary in temperature to measure leaf litter decomposition. This example is not as contrived as it seems, some streams in Iceland vary from 5 degC to 25 degC within a kilometer of each other.

Synthesize data.

For a multilevel model, start at he top level and sythesize downward. In this case, we start with a temperature vs \(k\) model for streams \(j\). \[log(k_j)\sim normal( log (c) + (-0.65(\frac{1}{(K_B\times T_j)} - \frac{1}{(K_B\times 283.15)} ) ), \sigma_j)\] \(T\) is absolute temperature (K), \(c\) is a constant (set to 0.01), \(K_B\) is the Boltzmann constant. This function is called an Arrhenius function and should be familiar from courses in physiology. In case the above equation is too much, we can more simply write (ignoring the probability) \[k=c\times e^{\frac{-0.65}{K_B T}}\].
See Brown et al. 2004 Ecology for more information on this equation. The value 0.65 (units are eV) represents the activation energy for cellular respiration. It is roughly equal to a Q\(_{10}\) = 2 (which is something else I hope you remember from physiology)

Now, make a vector of \(k_j\) with some random normal error.

temp<- c(5,8,13,15,20,22)+273.15

KB<-8.61e-5
log.k.true<-   log (0.01* exp(-0.65* (1/(KB*temp) - 1/(KB*283.15)   ) ))

log.k.true.err<-log.k.true+rnorm(6, 0,0.25)
exp(log.k.true.err)
## [1] 0.005922677 0.007385107 0.016059633 0.016999118 0.024998520 0.047316865
time<- c( 5, 10, 20, 30, 45, 60, 75, 90, 120)

Now use these values of randomly chosen \(k_j\) to derive leaf mass data based on the well-known exponential decay model \(M_{t,j}=e^{-K_jt}\), and then make a dataframe.

samp_n<-length(time)

stream<-rep(1:6, each=samp_n)
kstream<-rep(log.k.true.err, each=samp_n)+ rnorm(60,0,0.1) #adding error in log, so multiplicative
mass<-exp(- (exp(kstream)*time))  #Since kstream is logged we need to exponentiate first

Kdf<- data.frame(stream=stream, kstream=kstream ,mass=mass, time= rep(time,6) )

A better way to fake the data: using the beta distribution

Here instead of generating random normal \(K\) we instead use the bata distribution. We can reparameterize the beta distribution such that \(\alpha = \mu \times \phi\) and \(\beta = (1-\mu) \times \phi\). \(\phi\) in this case relates to the variance. Play with it, I adjusted to get some amount of error in the data.

time<- c( 5, 10, 20, 30, 45, 60, 75, 90, 120)
samp_n<-length(time)
stream<-rep(1:6, each=samp_n)
kstream.true<-rep(log.k.true.err, each=samp_n) 
mass.true<-exp(- (exp(kstream.true)*time)) #exponetial decay
phi=60
alpha<-mass.true*phi
beta<-  (1-mass.true)*phi
mass<- rbeta(length(kstream.true), alpha, beta )
Kdf<- data.frame(stream=stream, kstream=kstream.true ,mass=mass, time= rep(time,6) )

ggplot(Kdf, aes(time, mass)) + 
  geom_point() +
   geom_line(data = Kdf, aes(x = time, y = mass.true), color="blue")+
  facet_wrap(. ~ stream)

There are the data. Blue line is the true data

The Stan model

The model we use is:

sink("mult_decomp_beta.stan")

cat("
    
    data {
    int<lower = 1> N;
    int<lower = 1> nstreams;
    int<lower = 1> streamID[N];
    vector[N] time;
    vector[N] mass;
    vector[nstreams] temp;
    real KB;
    }
    
    parameters {
    vector <upper = 0> [nstreams] logk;    
    //real <lower = 0> intercept;
    real<lower = 0.1> phi; //  
    real slope_k_T;
    real int_k_T;
    real <lower = 0> sigma_stream;
    
    
    }
    
    transformed parameters{
    
    vector <lower=0.00001> [nstreams] k; 
     vector <lower=0, upper=1>[N] yhat; 
      vector <lower=0 > [N] alpha;
     vector <lower=0 > [N] B;


k=exp(logk);
    
for (i in 1:N){
      yhat[i]= 1 * exp(-k[streamID[i]]*time[i]);
       alpha[i] = yhat[i]*phi;
      B[i] = (1-yhat[i])*phi;
}
      
        
    
    }
    model {
    for (i in 1:N){
    mass[i] ~ beta(alpha[i],B[i]); // likelihood
    }
    for (j in 1:nstreams){
    logk[j]~normal( log(int_k_T) + slope_k_T * (1/(KB*temp[j]) - 1/(KB*283.15)   ) , sigma_stream);
    }
    
    int_k_T ~normal(0,0.1);
    slope_k_T~normal(0,1);
    sigma_stream~normal (0,2);
    
    }
    
    "
    ,fill=TRUE)
sink()

Lots going on here, we will discuss in class. But first, you may wonder about this likelihood. Fist consider the data? what are there ranges? Since decomposition is a proportion of the initial mass of leaves in the bag, the proportion must fall into 0 to 1. No way we can measure negative mass. Even though 99.9% of these studies will use normal distribution on exponential data or, God forbid log transformed data (a problem because error is roughly constant with time and mass, so logging will increase variation with time). So what do we use? Beta distribution. But like Gamma, the parameters in beta \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) do not really have much meaning. So we will use the \(\mu\) and \(\phi\) reparameterization of beta where $= $ and \(\beta = (1-\mu)\times \phi\). Phi is a dispersion parameter. If you need to know the variance, you can estimate \(\mu\) and variance as a function of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), but the algebra is hairy (p 68 in H&H). Reparameterizing odd distributions by their moments is standard practice, so study this topic. Note all the constraints in the model. Leave those constraints out and Stan will crash. Try to initialze fake data where day 1 has probability of 1 and Stan will crash too (\(pdf=\infty\), I once lost a Monday to this tiny problem).

Make a list (I did this for you) and run the model

decomp.dat<- list( N= length(Kdf$stream), nstreams=6, streamID=Kdf$stream, time=Kdf$time, mass=Kdf$mass, temp=temp, KB=8.61e-5)

fit <- stan("/Users/bob.hall/ecomodels/mult_decomp_beta.stan", data = decomp.dat,  iter = 1000, chains = 4)

Temp vs k plot

Now plot temp vs k and then and the error on the regression fit. I hope you have a strong stomach.

tempcorr<-(1/(KB*temp) - 1/(KB*283.15)   )
logk_sum<- summary(fit, pars="logk")$summary
slope_int_sum<- summary(fit, pars=c("slope_k_T", "int_k_T "))$summary

samples_fit<- rstan::extract(fit, pars=c("slope_k_T ", "int_k_T" ))

plot (tempcorr, logk_sum[,1] )
for (i in 1:1000){
  lines(tempcorr, log(samples_fit$int_k_T[i]) + samples_fit$slope_k_T[i]*tempcorr, col='light gray')
}
points (tempcorr, logk_sum[,1], col='blue', pch=16)
lines(tempcorr, log(slope_int_sum[2,1]) +slope_int_sum[1,1]*tempcorr, col="blue" )

A few things to take away

  1. There is low error within streams, thus the estimates of \(k_j\) are robust to the prior. That is, the likelihood wins.

  2. But what about the value that we really care about, the slope of the k vs T? In the hierarchical model the slope mean = -0.7911429 and CI are (-1.0027948, -0.5406841). That is a lot of variation and is because of the within stream variation in proportion mass remaining. Even though it is low, it matters in the overall parameter estimates. I spent some time looking and could find no study that estimated leaf brerakdown this way in streams. Nearly all calculate the decay coefficient, \(K\) and then proceed to do statistics on that values as if it were a data point. This procedure is conceptually incorrect.
